 creators currently lack the legal ability to compel attribution for their work, to prevent misattribution, and to safeguard their work from unwanted modifications. Drawing from a number of diverse sources, including literary, philosophical, and religious works, this book offers real solutions for crafting legal measures that facilitate an author's ability to safeguard his or her work without entirely sacrificing the intellectual property policies in practice in the United States today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAuthorsxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aAuthorsxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aCopyrightxMoral rightsxUnited States. 0aCopyrightxMoral rightszUnited States. 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.)xUSAxUnited States. 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 7aLAW / Intellectual Property / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804773416zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804773416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804773416.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles